  "summary": "# Weekly Market Briefing \u2014 Week Ending April 5, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 1. Market Overview\n\nBroad equities posted a strong week across the board. **SPY gained +3.43%** to $655.83, while **QQQ outperformed at +3.98%**, signaling a risk-on, growth-favoring environment. Small caps (IWM +3.37%) and the Dow (DIA +3.03%) participated but lagged tech-heavy indices. VTI (+3.41%) and VOO (+3.44%) tracked closely with SPY, confirming broad-based participation. This was a convincingly positive week with no major index left behind \u2014 though notable divergences emerged beneath the surface.\n\n## 2. Sector Performance\n\n**Outperformers:**\n- **Technology (XLK +4.67%)** led sectors, consistent with QQQ's outperformance and driven by mega-cap strength.\n- **Communication Services (XLC +4.35%)** rode gains in META and GOOGL.\n- **Real Estate (XLRE +4.00%)** rallied alongside falling rate expectations, with TLT gaining +1.75%.\n- **Financials (XLF +3.60%)** showed strength, potentially anticipating earnings season.\n\n**Underperformers:**\n- **Energy (XLE -5.29%)** was the clear laggard and the only sector in the red, likely pressured by falling crude oil prices. XOM (-6.02%) and CVX (-5.77%) saw heavy selling.\n- **Consumer Staples (XLP +0.13%)** were essentially flat \u2014 classic defensive rotation out as risk appetite returned.\n- **Utilities (XLU +1.65%)** also lagged, reinforcing the growth-over-safety narrative.\n\n## 3. Notable Movers\n\n- **META (+9.27%)** was the week's standout, surging on high volume \u2014 the largest gain among mega-caps tracked. At a P/E of 24.4, it remains relatively reasonable for its growth profile.\n- **GOOGL (+7.81%)** and **AMD (+7.68%)** also posted outsized gains, suggesting renewed AI/semiconductor enthusiasm.\n- **COIN (+6.40%)** rallied despite crypto weakness (BTC -1.72%, ETH -4.66%), an interesting divergence worth monitoring.\n- **TSLA (-0.34%)** was notably flat amid the rally, with a P/E of 333.9 that continues to stand out.\n- **XOM (-6.02%)** and **T (-2.65%)** were among the weakest names, reflecting energy/telecom pressure.\n- **GLD (+3.55%)** and **SLV (+3.70%)** both rallied alongside equities \u2014 an unusual pairing that may reflect persistent inflation hedging or geopolitical demand.\n\n## 4. Key Metrics\n\n- **Valuation concern:** PLTR (P/E 239.5), TSLA (333.9), and SHOP (127.2) carry extreme multiples that leave little room for disappointment.\n- **Encouraging:** MSFT (P/E 23.4), GOOGL (27.4), and META (24.4) look reasonable relative to growth rates.\n- **Crypto broadly weak:** All eight tracked crypto assets declined, with ETH (-4.66%) and XRP (-4.49%) leading losses \u2014 a notable divergence from risk-on equity sentiment.\n- **Bonds firming:** TLT (+1.75%) and BND (+0.99%) suggest the market is pricing in dovish Fed expectations.\n\n## 5. Themes to Watch\n\n- **Equities + bonds + gold all rising** simultaneously is unusual \u2014 watch for which leg breaks first.\n- **Energy sector collapse** warrants attention: is this an oil supply story or demand concern?\n- **Crypto-equity divergence** \u2014 risk appetite in stocks isn't translating to digital assets.\n- **Q1 earnings season** kicks off soon; financials report first. Elevated multiples across growth names raise the bar.\n- **Rate expectations** implied by the TLT rally could shift quickly on any hot inflation data.\n\n---\n\n*This briefing is for informational purposes only. No buy/sell recommendations are included.*",
